          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>Which unique feature of the olfactory pathway distinguishes it from all other se</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Which unique feature of the olfactory pathway distinguishes it from all other sensory systems?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>It uses receptor cells that cannot regenerate after birth</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Incorrect. Olfactory receptor cells are actually the only neurons in the adult brain that regenerate — a unique and clinically important feature.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>It relays through the ventral posteromedial nucleus of the thalamus</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Incorrect. The VPM nucleus is part of the gustatory (taste) pathway. The olfactory pathway uniquely bypasses the thalamus entirely.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>It projects directly to the cortex without a thalamic relay</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct! Olfactory signals bypass the thalamus and reach the primary olfactory cortex and limbic system directly, which is why smell is so powerfully linked to emotion and memory.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>It is mediated by free nerve endings rather than specialised receptors</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Incorrect. Olfaction uses specialised modified bipolar neurons in the olfactory epithelium, with cilia that detect odour molecules in the nasal mucus.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The olfactory pathway is the only sensory system that reaches the cortex without relaying through the thalamus. This direct limbic connection is why a familiar smell can instantly trigger vivid emotional memories."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done! The olfactory pathway's direct projection to the limbic system, without a thalamic relay, is unique among all sensory systems and explains the powerful connection between smell and emotional memory."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
                "enableRetry": true,
