          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>The vestibular apparatus serves balance through two functionally distinct compon</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>The vestibular apparatus serves balance through two functionally distinct components. Which structures specifically detect linear acceleration and the position of the head relative to gravity?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>The three semicircular canals</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Incorrect. The semicircular canals detect rotational (angular) head movements, not linear acceleration or gravity.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The utricle and saccule</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct! The utricle and saccule are the otolith organs. They contain tiny crystals that shift with gravity and linear acceleration, stimulating the underlying hair cells to signal head position.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The organ of Corti on the basilar membrane</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Incorrect. The organ of Corti sits within the cochlea and is the sensory organ for hearing, not balance.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The cochlear hair cells and auditory nerve</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Incorrect. Cochlear hair cells and the auditory nerve are part of the hearing pathway. The vestibular hair cells and vestibulocochlear nerve handle balance.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The otolith organs — utricle and saccule — detect linear acceleration and gravity. The semicircular canals detect rotational movements. Both are essential parts of the vestibular apparatus within the inner ear."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Excellent! The utricle detects horizontal linear acceleration while the saccule detects vertical linear acceleration. Together with the semicircular canals, they form the complete vestibular apparatus."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
                "enableRetry": true,
