          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>A patient with a pituitary tumour develops loss of the temporal visual fields in</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>A patient with a pituitary tumour develops loss of the temporal visual fields in both eyes (bitemporal hemianopia). Which fibres are compressed at the optic chiasma to produce this pattern?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Temporal retinal fibres from both eyes</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Incorrect. Temporal fibres do not cross at the chiasma — they stay on the same side (ipsilateral). A midline tumour cannot selectively compress them.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Nasal retinal fibres from both eyes</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct! Nasal retinal fibres cross at the chiasma. Since nasal retina receives the temporal visual field, compressing both crossing nasal bundles from below causes loss of both temporal fields — bitemporal hemianopia.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>All fibres from the ipsilateral optic nerve</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Incorrect. Complete optic nerve compression would cause total blindness in one eye, not bilateral temporal field loss. A pituitary tumour presses upward on the chiasma from below, affecting the crossing fibres.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Macular fibres from the contralateral eye only</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Incorrect. Macular fibre damage alone would impair central vision, not produce the characteristic bilateral temporal field loss of chiasmal compression.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "At the optic chiasma, nasal retinal fibres cross to the opposite side while temporal fibres remain ipsilateral. A pituitary tumour pressing from below compresses both crossing nasal bundles, producing bitemporal hemianopia."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done! Understanding the partial decussation at the optic chiasma — nasal fibres cross, temporal fibres stay ipsilateral — is the key to localising visual pathway lesions clinically."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
